# MCP-First Workflow

Use MCP tools for implementation and verification before falling back to shell, memory, or guesswork.

## When to use MCP

| Task | MCP server | Examples |
|------|------------|----------|
| Supabase schema, migrations, RLS, data checks | `user-supabase` | `apply_migration`, `execute_sql`, `list_tables`, `list_migrations`, `get_advisors`, `get_logs`, `deploy_edge_function` |
| Flutter/Dart analysis, formatting, tests | `user-dart` | Prefer over raw `dart`/`flutter` shell when available |
| Library/framework docs | `user-context7` | API syntax, migrations, SDK changes |
| GitHub issues, PRs, checks | `user-github` | `gh`-backed operations |
| UI verification in browser | `cursor-ide-browser` | Snapshots, navigation, screenshots |

## Rules

- Read the MCP tool schema/descriptor before calling a tool.
- Apply Supabase migrations via `apply_migration` — do not ask Sean to run SQL manually when MCP can do it.
- Verify schema changes with `list_tables` or `execute_sql` after migrations.
- Check Edge Function / auth failures with `get_logs` before guessing root cause.
- Run `get_advisors` after meaningful schema or RLS changes.
- If an MCP call fails, diagnose and retry or report the blocker — do not silently skip verification.

## Fallback

Use shell only when no MCP tool covers the task (e.g. local `flutter run`, git) or MCP is unavailable.
